list.item:
Copies of news reports to Thomas Errington, retired merchant, August 26,
							1822-January 20, 1823, and other notes and copies of letters, April 17, 1923-January
							18, 1833. Pp. [189-199];

scopecontent.p:
United States. Louisville, Kentucky. To James Taylor, military agent, Newport,
						Kentucky. Recruiting; asks opinion of General Dearborn and news of other appointments;
						earthquake shocks.

Massachusetts. To Joseph Bradley Varnum, Washington, D.C. Glorious success of navy;
							amen to votes of Congress to augment it;
						dissatisfaction with unsuccessful manner in which war has been prosecuted on land; need
						40,000 regulars and as many volunteers as will join to enter the enemy’s territory.

Headquarters 4th military district, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, June 21-Aug.8, 1813;
						Headquarters, 5th military district, Washington, D.C., Aug. 23-Nov. 26, 1813; Camp Cold
						Spring, Sept. 10-Nov. 8, 1813.

Groton, Massachusetts. To Joseph Bradley, Varnum, Washington, D.C. Local affairs;
						resignation of Hampton, arrest of Wilkinson, removal of Granger; so disgraceful a campaign as our last was never known;
						politics.

Richmond, Virginia. To Messrs. Brown & Ives, Providence, Rhode Island. Unlikeliness
						of an attack on Richmond; destruction of most of tobacco crop by rain; prices;
						advisability of shipping in salt.

list.item:
The original was signed by Alexander Murray, as president of the Court of Inquiry;
							Henry Wheaton, as judge advocate; and approved by Benjamin Williams Crowninshield, as
							secretary of the navy.
